Variation. The color varies from blue to greenish and black. A few specimens appear bicolored, with the elytra blackish or purplish, with the pronotum having a purplish tint. In females, the basal tarsomeres are narrower than in males. The female mandibles are slightly smaller than the male (but not nearly as sexually dimorphic as in the similar genus
Metaparia
). The female fifth ventrite has a slightly ventrally curved tip, whereas the fifth ventrite in the male is flat. Male beetles ( n = 8) measure 2.8–3.4 mm in length; females ( n = 10) measure 2.8–3.5 mm in length.
